Yep, that's not quite right; you want to be able to provide a function that emits any element or you want to give it a component class that it can instantiate.  If you take a look at VirtualizedList.js, you can see how the prop is used to instantiate the component:

```if (ListHeaderComponent) {
      const element = React.isValidElement(ListHeaderComponent)
        ? ListHeaderComponent // $FlowFixMe
        : <ListHeaderComponent />;
      cells.push(
        <View key="$header" onLayout={this._onLayoutHeader}>
          {element}
        </View>
      );
    }
```

This allows usage like the following: 

```
renderHeader = () => {
 return <View />
}
```
and in the FlatList itself:
```
<FlatList
              data={this.props.data}
              renderItem={this.renderItem}
              keyExtractor={this.keyExtractor}
              ListHeaderComponent={this.renderHeader}
            />
```

An example of why the array needs to support undefined values:
```
interface MyComponentProps {
   extraStyle?: ViewStyle
}

function MyComponent(props: MyComponentProps) {
  const styles = [props.style, props.extraStyle];
  // styles is of type "(ViewStyle | undefined)[]"
  return <View style={styles} />;
}
```

This allows us to resolve original style type with ```Stylesheet.flatten```.

Example:
```typescript
const style = StyleSheet.create({
    welcome: {
        fontSize:  20,
        textAlign: 'center',
        margin:    10,
    } as TextStyle
})

const welcomeStyle = StyleSheet.flatten(style.welcome) // welcomeStyle is TextStyle
```

